Aromatic polyketide is a large group of natural products, they exhibit various biological activities including anti- bacterial and anticancer [1]. Many compounds of this group have already been developed as drugs for clinical use. For example, the anticancer agents such as dauno- mycin, adriamycin and mithramycin play important roles in oncotherapy, while the antibiotic tetracyclines are widely used to treat infection. Previous work has shown that they were assembled by type II polyketide synthase (PKS). The minimal type II PKS, which consist of KSα (ketosynthease), KSβ (chain length factor) and ACP (acyl carrier protein), usually involves utilization of acetyl CoA as a starter unit; then, iterative condensation of several malonyl CoA extenders to form a linear poly- ketide, which is followed by cyclization and aromatiza- tion to establish the backbone [2]. Diﬀerent type II polyketide compounds undergo various post-PKS tailor- ing reactions such as oxidation, reduction, and glycosyla- tion, which make them rich in chemical structure and diverse in biological activities. Based on the biosynthetic pathway study, genetic engineering tools were introduced to create promising new analogs [3]. Frigocyclinone was ﬁrst discovered in the fermen- tation broth of S. griseus strain NTK 97 which was it was also isolated from Antarctica [4]. Recently, found that marine sponge-associated Streptomyces sp. M7_15 produces [5]. Frigocyclinone belongs to the angucycline/angucycli- none subfamily which was featured by its polycyclic aromatic skeleton assembled in an angular manner. yyjj413@163.com; Huizhan Zhang Supplemental data for this article can be accessed here. © 2019 Japan Society for Bioscience, Biotechnology, and Agrochemistry

ABSTRACT Frigocyclinone is a novel antibiotic with antibacterial and anticancer activities. It is produced by both Antarctica-derived Streptomyces griseus NTK 97 and marine sponge-associated Streptomyces sp. M7_15. Here, we ﬁrst report the biosynthetic gene cluster of frigocyclinone in the S. griseus NTK 97. The frigocyclinone gene cluster spans a DNA region of 33-kb which consists of 30 open reading frames (ORFs), encoding minimal type II polyketide synthase, aromatase and cyclase, redox tailoring enzymes, sugar biosynthesis-related enzymes, C-glycosyltransferase, a resistance protein, and three regulatory proteins. Based on the bioinformatic analysis, a biosynthetic pathway for frigocyclinone was proposed. Second, to verify the cloned gene cluster, CRISPR-Cpf1 mediated gene disruption was conducted. Mutant with the disruption of beta-ketoacyl synthase encoding gene frig20 fully loses the ability of producing frigocyclinone, while inactivating the glycosyltransferase gene frig1 leads to the production of key intermediate of anti-MRSA anthraquinone tetrangomycin. Typical members of this family are landomycin [6] and urdamycin [7]. The chemical structure of frigo- cyclinone consists of an angucyclinone core linked with an aminodeoxysugar ossamine by a rare C-glycosidic bond as shown in Figure 1. Gram- and positive bacteria Staphylococcus aureus were sensitive to frigocyclinone at low concentration. Meanwhile, frigocyclinone can kill rhabdomyosarcoma cancer cells at EC50 of 5.2 μM after 48 h treatment, showing the potential to be used as antitumor drugs [5].

In order to improve the production of frigocycli- none and generate novel frigocyclinone-related com- pounds and genetic combinatorial biosynthesis [8], it is necessary to elu- cidate the biosynthetic pathways and regulation mechanisms of the antibiotics. Herein, we report: (i) cloning and sequencing of the biosynthetic gene clus- ter of frigocyclinone from the genome of S. griseus strain NTK 97; (ii) a proposed biosynthetic pathway for frigocyclinone through bioinformatic analysis; (iii) characterization and conﬁrmation of the frigocy- clinone gene cluster by gene disruption. E. coli JM83 [9] and EPI300 (Epicentre) were used as hosts for general gene cloning and genomic fosmid library construction, respectively. pMD18-T purchased from Takara was used as cloning vector. pKCCpf1 [10] was used for gene disruption. All E. coli strains were grown on solid or in liquid Luria-Bertani (LB) medium (yeast extract 5 g/L, sodium chloride 10 g/L, tryptone 10 g/L) at 37 °C. S. griseus strain NTK 97 and its mutant strains were cultured in tryptone soya broth (TSB) at 28°C for mycelium growth. For Streptomyces sporulation, the strains were grown on solid mannitol soya ﬂour (MS) medium (mannitol 20 g/L, soya ﬂour 20 g/L, agar 20 g/L). For conjugation, Streptomyces strains were grown on solid International Streptomyces Project Medium 4 (ISP4) medium (starch 10 g/L, K2HPO4 1 g/L, MgSO4 · 7H2O 1 g/L, (NH4)2·SO4 2 g/L, CaCO3 2 g/L, NaCl 1 g/L, FeSO4 1 mg/L, MnCl2 · 7H2O 1 mg/L, ZnSO4 · 7H2O 1 mg/L, agar 20 g/L) containing 80 mM MgCl2. The fermentation med- ium for frigocyclinone production contains glucose 10 g/L, starch 20 g/L, bacto peptone 3 g/L, meat extract 3 g/L, yeast extract 5 g/L, CaCO3 3 g/L. Proper antibiotics were added to the medium to a ﬁnal concentration of 100 μg/mL (ampicillin) and 50 μg/mL (apramycin), as required.

Generation of gene disruption mutant strains

CRISPR-Cpf1 was employed to the generation of the gene disruption mutant strain [12]. Target-speciﬁc crRNA was designed under the control of kasOp* to induce double-strand breaks, and then a homology- directed repair occurred with the editing plasmid [10]. The construction of the plasmids was shown in Figure 4 and the primers were listed in Table S1. The disruption plasmids were introduced into E. coli S17-1 by transformation, and then conjugated with spores of S. griseus strain NTK 97 [11]. The mutants were ﬁrst selected with the phenotype of resistance to apramycin, and then veriﬁed by PCR. The resulting mutant was subsequently grown in TSB medium without apramycin at 37 °C for three rounds to remove the disruption plasmids. Fermentation and HPLC analysis of S. griseus NTK 97 and mutant strains

S. griseus NTK 97 and mutant strains were ﬁrstly inocu- lated to TSB medium from petri dishes and cultured at 28 °C for 3 days. Two milliliters of seed medium was added to a 500-mL ﬂask which contains 50 mL fermen- tation medium. After 5 ~ 7 days fermentation at 28°C, the culture ﬁltrate was extracted with an equal volume of ethyl acetate. The organic phase was collected and subjected to vacuum rotary evaporation. The dried samples were re-dissolved in 1 mL methanol and ana- lyzed by HPLC-MS using ThermoScientiﬁc LTQ XL mass spectrometer with ThermoScientiﬁc Ultimate 3000 HPLC (ThermoScientiﬁc Acclaim 120 C18 5 μm, 4.6 × 250 mm). The samples were eluted with solvent A (H2O, 0.1% formic acid) and solvent B (CH3CN, 0.1% formic acid) with the gradient shown in Figure S2 at a ﬂow rate of 1 mL/min and UV detection at 269 nm. HR-ESI-MS was carried out on the ThermoFisher Scientiﬁc Q-Exactive MS System. NMR analysis was conducted at Agilent DD2 500 MHz nuclear magnetic resonance spectrometer. Nucleotide sequence accession number The nucleotide sequence of the frigocyclinone biosyn- thetic gene cluster was deposited into the GenBank database under accession number MK240316. Cloning of frigocyclinone biosynthetic gene cluster and bioinformatics analysis

By analyzing the structure of frigocyclinone, the fri- gocyclinone biosynthesis gene cluster was deduced to encode dNDP-hexose-4, 6-dehydratase which is responsible for the synthesis of the deoxyhexose moi- ety [13]. Thus, a pair of degenerated primers, P1 and P2 was designed to amplify the conserved region of NDP-hexose-4, 6-dehydratase as shown in Figure S1 [14]. PCR products were ligated to pMD18-T vector and three randomly selected clones were subse- quently sent for sequencing. All the sequence of the inserted fragment from these three subclones were identical and showed high homology to the known dNDP-hexose-4, 6-dehydratase (72.6% identity to JadT and 69.9% identity to UrdH). CLONING AND IDENTIFICATION OF THE FRIGOCYCLINONE BGC In order to clone the frigocyclinone gene cluster, a genomic library of S. griseus strain NTK 97 was con- structed. Two fosmids (3B2 and 5D1) were selected from the library using the degenerated primers mentioned before and subsequently submitted for sequencing. Besides the cloned conserved region of dNDP-hexose-4, 6-dehydratase, there were several genes related to deox- ysugar synthesis. Meanwhile, typical type II PKS genes were in the ﬂanking regions. These data showed that the type II PKS cluster and its ﬂanking regions may be involved in the biosynthesis of frigocyclinone. Thus, we named this the “frig” gene cluster.

The frig gene cluster spans a DNA region of ~33 kb which was predicted to contain 30 ORFs (Table 2) through FramePlot 4.0 beta [15] and NCBI BLAST pro- grams. The organization of the frig gene cluster is shown in Figure 2. Identiﬁed genes include those are responsible for the biosynthesis of deoxyhexose, assemble of the angucyclinone backbone, sugar moiety transfer, self- resistance of frigocyclinone.

Based on the genetic information obtained from sequencing, we proposed a pathway for frigocycli- none biosynthesis (Figure 3). The predicted amino acid sequences of Frig18, Frig19, Frig20 show high similarity with known type II miniPKS such as land- omycin [16], jadomycin [17] and urdamycin [7]. The beta-ketoacyl synthase (Frig20, 83.0% identity to LanA), chain length factor (Frig19, 74.6% identity to LanB) and acyl carrier protein (Frig18, 61.8% identity to LanC) make up the minimal PKS to produce decapolyketide (1). The gene product of frig17 (ketor- eductase, 83.4% identity to PgaD) was predicted to catalyze the reduction of linear polyketide to trans- form 1 to 2, and Frig16 (aromatase, 76.9% identity to PgaL) was predicted to be responsible for the aro- matic ring systems formation to yield 3. Cyclase Frig21 (82.6% identity to PgaY) was predicted to be involved in the last two ring formation to yield early intermediate UWM6 (4). And then, UWM6 (4) undergoes several post-PKS tailoring steps with the involvement of oxidoreductase encoded by genes frig25. First, Frig22, a homolog of frig15, PgaE (82.3% identity) which is an NADPH- dependent ﬂavoprotein hydroxylase, was predicted to catalyze two consecutive oxygen-dependent reac- tions to form 6 [18]. Frig15 (72.8% identity to PgaM) was predicted to be a bifunctional oxygenase/reduc- tase with an N-terminal ﬂavin-dependent oxygenase domain and a C-terminal reductase domain which belongs to SDR superfamily [19]. It was predicted to be involved in the transformation from 6 to the ﬁnal aglycone tetrangomycin (9) [20,21]. Frig25 was pre- an NADPH-dependent

The gene product of frig5, homologous to typical dTDP- hexose 3,5-epimerase [24], was involved in the trans- formation of 14 to 15. Frig8, a homologue of SpnQ [25], was predicted to mediate the C-3 deoxygenation to form 16. Frig4 was a putative dTDP-hexose ami- notransferase involved in the transformation of 16 to 17. Two methyl groups were sequentially transferred to 17 by Frig3 (N, N-dimethyltransferase) [26] to yield dTDP-ossamine (19). Sugar moiety is usually attached to the aglycone through O- or N-glycosyl transferase, rare cases of C-glycosyl transferase were reported [27,28]. Based on the analysis of the chemical structure of frigocy- clinone, C-glucosylation was believed to be involved in its biosynthesis. There was only one putative glycosyltransferase gene in the frig cluster, frig1, which suggests it is responsible for the formation of the C-glycosidic linkage between ossamine and tetrangomycin. CLONING AND IDENTIFICATION OF THE FRIGOCYCLINONE BGC There were three putative regulatory genes located in the frig gene cluster, frig23, frig29 and frig30. Both of frig23 and frig29 were deduced to encode response reg- ulator in the two-component system, while frig30 was predicted to be a member of TetR transcription regula- tion family. Only one resistance gene was found in the cluster, which was frig4 belonging to the major facilitator superfamily. Veriﬁcation of the frig gene cluster by gene disruption

To verify the involvement of these genes in frigocyclinone biosynthesis, frig20 encoding one of the beta-ketoacyl synthase subunits was inactivated through CRISPR-Cpf 1 mediated gene disruption. The deletion of frig20 is illustrated in Figure 4(a). PCR primers used to identify the mutant were designed outside the homologous arms. The PCR products in Figure 4(b) showed the frig20 was disrupted from the chromosome of NTK 97. This result was further conﬁrmed by sequencing the PCR product. Figure 4. (c) PCR analysis of the Δfrig1 mutant. lane 1, DNA ladder; lane 2, PCR product of the wild-type; Lane 3, PCR product of Δfrig1 The mutant Δfrig20 completely loses the ability to pro- duce frigocyclinone through HPLC analysis of the fer- mentation broth of the mutant (Figure 5(b)) compared to wild type (Figure 5(a)). These results indicated the frig20 is indispensable for the frigocyclinone biosynthesis. Combined with bioinformatic analysis obtained above, it is concluded that the cloned frig cluster is responsible for the biosynthesis of frigocyclinone. Figure 5. Figure 6. Structural determination of compound A. (a) LC-HRMS spectrum of compound A. (b) 1H-1H correlation spectroscopy (COSY) and 1H-13C heteronuclear multiple bond correlation (HMBC) analysis of compound A fermentation broth of the mutant Δfrig1 showed the accumulation of a new compound A (Figure 5(c)). To conﬁrm the chemical structure of this new com- pound, compound A was puriﬁed from 2 L of fer- mentation broth of Δfrig1. About 15 mg of pure compound A was obtained. The exact mass of [M + H]+ ion was found at m/z 323.0905 (Figure 6(a)) for the molecular formula C19H14O5 (calculated for C19 H15O5: 323.0919, Δmmu −0.920). Structure analysis was ﬁrst performed by 1H NMR (Figure S3a) and 13C NMR (Figure S3b); the chemical shift of hydro- gen and carbon are summarized in Table S2 and compared to those reported in the literature [21]. Combined with 1H-1H COSY and 1H-13C HMBC NMR spectra of compound A (Figure 6(b), detailed see Figure S3c-e), the chemical structure of com- pound A was determined as tetrangomycin as expected. These results indicated that Frig1 is a novel C-glycosyltransferase. Glycosyltransferase plays an important role in the biosynthesis of a large number of natural products, contributing to their diversiﬁca- tion and activity. Most natural products are linked to their sugar moieties by O-glycosidic bond, which makes them sensitive to hydrolysis, limiting their therapeutic application. However, the C-glycosidic bond formed between aglycone and sugar moieties is chemically more stable. In this study, the novel C-Glycosyltransferase frig1 may add to the glycodi- versiﬁcation toolbox to produce new natural products.

Frigocyclinone is a novel natural product from S. griseus strain NTK 97. Despite its intriguing chemical structure, little is known about the bio- synthesis information. In this study, we reported the isolation of frigocyclinone biosynthetic cluster from the genomic library of S. griseus strain NTK 97. In order to gain more information, shotgun CLONING AND IDENTIFICATION OF THE FRIGOCYCLINONE BGC sequencing of the two selected fosmids was con- ducted. Bioinformatic cluster allowed us to propose a biosynthetic pathway of frigocyclinone. Two key genes frig1 and frig20, responsible for the C-glycosidic bond formation and PKS synthesis, respectively, were disrupted to the key verify the cloned cluster. Meanwhile, intermediate tetrangomycin was separated and identiﬁed through LC-HRMS and NMR. We are grateful to Prof. Hans-Peter Fiedler for the kind gift of Streptomyces griseus strain NTK 97.
